Model 1 - The Economy on Skiing

We are initially beginning with a model including CPI, annual income for Summit County, and the unemployment rate in Summit County. We will additionally be lagging the skier visits per year by one year to account for season pass holders and ski trip planners. Public sentiment to skiing can be effected in the half year before the season starts between summer and winter, thus, we must lag our data to account for this. All definitions of data can be found on page xx of the paper.

model1_a <- dynlm(Visitors.by.Acres~
                  lag(Visitors.by.Acres,1)+
                  log(CPI)+
                  Annual.Income..Summit.+
                  Unemployment.Rate..Summit.County.
                  ,
             data=timeseries)
summary(model1_a)

Model1_a provides results for significance of annual income in Summit County, but no significance for other results. We can attempt to just model CPI and Income to account for spending rather than unemployment. We will now remove unemployment and just evaluate monetary values to see if there is a difference.

model1_b <- dynlm(Visitors.by.Acres~
                  lag(Visitors.by.Acres,1)+
                  CPI+
                  Annual.Income..Colorado.
                  ,
             data=timeseries)

Intersting enough, Model1_b actually provides less significant results meaning that unemployment is a major factor in skier visits per year. We will now isolate these two variables for their own linear regression. See model1_c below for unemployment and model1_d for CPI.
